{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "However, one can find specific twist angles that yield a commensurate and periodic superlattice via the following construction.",
    "Let a G1 and a G2 be the unrotated monolayer primitive lattice vectors, and R θ be a rotation matrix about the stacking axis.",
    "If there exist integers m i, n i that are not all vanishing such that m 1 R θ/2 a G1 + m 2 R θ/2 a G2 = n 1 R -θ/2 a G1 + n 2 R -θ/2 a G2, then the combined system has discrete translation invariance [115].",
    "Note that the statement of commensurability only depends on θ and not the interlayer shift d. From an experimental standpoint, such considerations are largely irrelevant: it is impossible to determine whether a given sample has a commensurate twist, let alone deliberately fabricate a device with a precise twist.",
    "Theoretically, of course, it very helpful to be able to leverage the machinery of Bloch's theorem and think in terms of crystal momenta."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "If there exist integers m i, n i that are not all vanishing such that m 1 R θ/2 a G1 + m 2 R θ/2 a G2 = n 1 R -θ/2 a G1 + n 2 R -θ/2 a G2, then the combined system has discrete translation invariance [115]."
  ]
}